00:02:05.634 --> 00:02:07.645
a link for those in the description.

00:02:07.735 --> 00:02:12.325
Question number two is, how do you
set up your fonts in such a way that

00:02:12.325 --> 00:02:16.075
it actually improves your design
and makes your site easier to use?

00:02:16.465 --> 00:02:20.275
If you've ever looked at a site
that was designed by a true web pro,

00:02:20.275 --> 00:02:21.715
you're gonna notice something, right?

00:02:21.715 --> 00:02:22.615
All the text fields.

00:02:22.975 --> 00:02:27.715
Cohesive yet predictable without
feeling super robotic, like you're

00:02:27.715 --> 00:02:29.575
kind of reading a Wikipedia page.

00:02:30.234 --> 00:02:34.644
That's because pro designers use
something called a type scale system,

00:02:34.674 --> 00:02:38.334
and it's just a simple set of rules
that determines things like font

00:02:38.334 --> 00:02:41.125
sizes, letter spacing, and line height.

00:02:41.125 --> 00:02:44.620
And once you've set it up, your
typography starts to feel intentional

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:46.435
instead of just eyeballed.

00:02:46.465 --> 00:02:48.415
Let's start with font size.

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:54.250
What you wanna do is pick a base
font size for your paragraph text.

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:59.440
Typically, people start with about 16
pixels, and then you use a scale to

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:02.080
make your headings consistently larger.

00:03:02.110 --> 00:03:05.890
A popular one is called the Major Third
Scale, and if you've ever learned.

00:03:06.205 --> 00:03:09.175
An instrument, this might
sound a little bit familiar.

00:03:09.535 --> 00:03:14.965
All it means is that you're actually
going to scale up in size from

00:03:15.055 --> 00:03:18.235
one text to the next by about 25%.

00:03:18.235 --> 00:03:21.506
So if your base size is
16, your H six would be.

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:27.450
20, and then your H five would be
25, so on and, and so forth until you

00:03:27.450 --> 00:03:32.130
reach your H ones and you actually
don't have to calculate this manually.

00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:37.410
Instead of using pixels, just use
the REM values, it does all the

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:39.750
calculations right there for you.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:43.140
Next up is letter spacing
for, for body text.

00:03:43.140 --> 00:03:44.070
Don't touch it, right?

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:47.640
We want that to be super legible
and so just keep it the default.

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:50.790
But for headings, you wanna
tighten it up a little bit.

00:03:50.825 --> 00:03:55.174
As they get bigger, as text gets
larger, it often looks cleaner

00:03:55.174 --> 00:03:57.185
with slightly reduced spacing.

00:03:57.304 --> 00:04:00.725
And then finally, line
height for paragraphs go with

00:04:00.725 --> 00:04:03.725
about 150% of the font size.

00:04:03.725 --> 00:04:08.885
So if the font size is 16 pixels, then
you would take that and then multiply it

00:04:08.885 --> 00:04:13.039
by 1.5 to get your line height that gives
the text room to breathe and makes it.

00:04:13.330 --> 00:04:14.410
Easier to read.

00:04:14.410 --> 00:04:18.490
And then as text gets bigger, like
with headings, you can tighten up

00:04:18.490 --> 00:04:22.540
the line height a bit to make it feel
a bit more impactful and scannable.

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:25.480
Now, if all that sounds like
a lot, here's a shortcut.

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:27.160
Go to type scale.net.

00:04:27.310 --> 00:04:28.630
You pick your base size.

00:04:29.060 --> 00:04:33.410
Choose a ratio and then it just
generates the whole system for you.

00:04:33.410 --> 00:04:36.950
It takes two minutes and makes
your typography look like a pro.

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:37.610
Set it up.

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:39.230
Next up is layout.

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:43.970
Most new web designers just kind of
drag things around until it feels right,

00:04:43.970 --> 00:04:47.570
and hey, you might even be following
some design rules without realizing,

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:51.770
but pro designers don't guess about
where things should go on the page.

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:53.750
They have systems that guarantee it.

00:04:53.914 --> 00:04:57.094
Every time, and you actually don't
need to memorize a ton of layout rules.

00:04:57.125 --> 00:04:58.685
You just need three things.

00:04:58.745 --> 00:05:03.335
A grid system for structure, a spacing
system for rhythm between elements

00:05:03.335 --> 00:05:08.104
and even vertical spacing, and then
visual hierarchy to guide the eye.

00:05:08.465 --> 00:05:10.145
Let's start with the grid.

00:05:10.175 --> 00:05:12.635
Think of this as your layouts foundation.

00:05:12.664 --> 00:05:14.650
I like to use a 12
column layout on desktop.

00:05:15.155 --> 00:05:19.475
Eight columns on tablets and
then four columns on mobile.

00:05:19.805 --> 00:05:20.555
Why is that?

00:05:20.555 --> 00:05:24.844
Well, because it's super flexible
to divide evenly to where you don't

00:05:24.844 --> 00:05:27.125
have to have 12 columns specifically.

00:05:27.125 --> 00:05:30.125
It could be two columns that
take up six columns on the right

00:05:30.125 --> 00:05:31.355
and six columns on the left.

00:05:31.715 --> 00:05:33.695
And then you can make it three or four.

00:05:33.695 --> 00:05:35.525
It's just easy to work with.

00:05:35.585 --> 00:05:38.435
FMA actually makes this
super simple to set up.

00:05:38.495 --> 00:05:42.605
All you have to do is select your
frame, come all the way down to layout

00:05:42.605 --> 00:05:46.685
guide, add the plus sign, change grid
to columns, and then add the amount of

00:05:46.685 --> 00:05:48.575
columns that you're wanting to work with.

00:05:48.914 --> 00:05:53.625
Next up is spacing, and this is what
gives your design room to breathe.

00:05:53.715 --> 00:05:57.734
I use what's called an eight point grid
system, and it just means that your

00:05:57.734 --> 00:06:04.905
spacing is always multiples of eight,
like 8, 16, 24, 32, so on and so forth.

00:06:04.935 --> 00:06:10.365
It's the same approach that's used by
Google for material design and Apple

00:06:10.365 --> 00:06:12.525
in in their design systems as well.

00:06:12.525 --> 00:06:15.044
And if major players like
Google and Apple are using it.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:17.210
Then you know you can't ignore it.

00:06:17.270 --> 00:06:19.580
This is also super easy to set up.

00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:23.390
You do the same thing in Figma as if
you're setting up columns, but then

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:28.070
when you add a guide, you just remain
on grid and then change the size of the

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:30.470
grid to whatever you're wanting to use.

00:06:30.590 --> 00:06:33.590
The last piece is visual
hierarchy, because here's the

00:06:33.590 --> 00:06:35.870
truth, people don't read websites.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:36.410
They scan them.

00:06:37.050 --> 00:06:40.020
So your layout needs to guide
the eyes from the things that

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:44.160
are most important to things that
maybe don't matter all that much.

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:46.890
Here are a few quick
principles to do just that.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:51.720
Use proximity, so keep related
things close together as if they're

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:54.390
in the same space on a page.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:59.760
Then use size to tell users what's
more important or least important.

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:03.960
You can see that this website's done
a good job with that on their big.

00:07:04.020 --> 00:07:08.549
Text and the big image down
here use contrast, right?

00:07:08.549 --> 00:07:13.380
You can use size, weight, or color, and
you can see that this website's done

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:18.120
that really well with the opacity of
their headers versus their body text.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:21.930
So they're signaling to you that they
really want you to read this and this

00:07:21.930 --> 00:07:24.479
other stuff might not be that important.

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:28.680
And then alignment, because
clean lines always equal.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.250
A clear structure.

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:33.760
When you use those four together,
you're gonna build a layout that feels

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:38.050
effortless to navigate, and that's what
separates the pros from the beginners.

00:07:38.140 --> 00:07:39.790
Next up, let's talk about color.

00:07:39.850 --> 00:07:43.240
For a lot of designers, this is
where things start to feel really

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.390
overwhelming because there are
millions of colors out there.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:48.070
So how do you know what works?

00:07:48.340 --> 00:07:49.270
Here's the secret.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.150
Pro designers don't use more color.

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:54.640
They use color more intentionally.

00:07:54.700 --> 00:07:58.540
Let me show you some quick wins that are
gonna instantly level up your color game.

00:07:58.570 --> 00:08:01.720
First, you want to limit
your color palette, right?

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:07.270
You don't need more than like two or three
different colors for any project that

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:09.580
you're working on, but here's the key.

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:12.190
Each one should have a specific.

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:12.920
Job.

00:08:13.250 --> 00:08:16.100
One of the most popular systems
for creating visual balance

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:18.710
is called the 60 30 10 rule.

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:22.100
So 60% are your neutral colors.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:24.290
Those are things like your
whites and your blacks.

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:27.050
You use that for your
background and your text.

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:30.915
30% are your secondary colors, and
you use those for maybe different.

00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:34.170
Backgrounds or cards, headers or visuals.

00:08:34.289 --> 00:08:39.300
And then finally, the 10% is your
accent colors, and that's what you

00:08:39.300 --> 00:08:43.500
use if you want something to really
stand out like buttons or CTAs.

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:44.880
But that's all you need really.

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:48.150
As you get more confident with
color, you can expand your palettes,

00:08:48.150 --> 00:08:50.100
but don't feel like you need to.

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:54.510
Another tip is use opacity
rather than adding more colors.

00:08:54.555 --> 00:08:55.635
To your palette.

00:08:55.635 --> 00:09:00.224
So take your primary color, like
this yellow here, and then just

00:09:00.224 --> 00:09:04.875
scroll down on the opacity to
create different color layers.

00:09:04.995 --> 00:09:07.724
This is something that I actually
learned when I was looking through

00:09:07.755 --> 00:09:11.594
Google's material design and noticed
that they used opacity to create a

00:09:11.594 --> 00:09:13.214
lot of different color variations.

00:09:13.214 --> 00:09:16.520
So one good color used well
beats five random colors.

00:09:16.945 --> 00:09:17.545
Any day.

00:09:17.785 --> 00:09:21.835
Next, you wanna prioritize contrast,
and this one's huge and it's one

00:09:21.835 --> 00:09:23.575
that a lot of new designers miss.

00:09:23.605 --> 00:09:27.475
Your color combo might look nice,
but if your users can't read it,

00:09:27.475 --> 00:09:29.275
it doesn't matter how pretty it is.

00:09:29.275 --> 00:09:32.185
So always check your color Contrast.

00:09:32.215 --> 00:09:36.295
Color contrast is the contrast
between your foreground text and.

00:09:36.770 --> 00:09:40.970
Background color that it sits on and,
and you can see here that passable

00:09:40.970 --> 00:09:47.210
contrast is three to one on larger
text and 4.5 to one on smaller text.

00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:51.020
Figma has a contrast checker
baked right into its color system.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:54.860
All you gotta do is select the text
that you want to check, go to fill,

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:58.490
and then there's a contrast icon
right in the top right hand corner.

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:01.400
It'll tell you whether or
not it passes or doesn't.

00:10:01.430 --> 00:10:02.390
It's a great tool.

00:10:02.450 --> 00:10:04.820
Finally, don't build color
palettes from scratch.

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:07.610
Most great color palettes
weren't made out of thin air.

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:09.770
They were borrowed and then refined.

00:10:09.800 --> 00:10:14.330
You can actually find any sites color
palette with a tool called CSS Overview.

00:10:14.450 --> 00:10:19.100
All you've gotta do is go to Chrome
Developer Tools and then select

00:10:19.130 --> 00:10:22.575
the three dot option right here
in the top right hand corner.

00:10:22.905 --> 00:10:26.895
Scroll down, go to more tools,
and then you'll see CSS overview.

00:10:27.194 --> 00:10:31.785
Capture the overview, and then it'll give
you all the colors for that specific site.

00:10:31.785 --> 00:10:35.475
It even gives you fonts,
it gives you size settings.

00:10:35.475 --> 00:10:37.095
It gives you the type scale system.

00:10:37.125 --> 00:10:39.015
It's such a great tool to use.

00:10:39.075 --> 00:10:40.305
Now let's talk code.

00:10:40.365 --> 00:10:44.025
And I know code Boo hiss,
we don't need that anymore.

00:10:44.055 --> 00:10:45.015
But here's the truth.

00:10:45.075 --> 00:10:48.045
If you want to be better than 99%
of the other web designers out

00:10:48.045 --> 00:10:51.495
there, you're gonna need to at
least get comfortable with it.

00:10:51.495 --> 00:10:54.075
But you don't need to know
how to build a full web app.

00:10:54.135 --> 00:10:56.730
You just need to know the basics
and then know how to use the right.

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:59.750
Tools to get you the rest of the way.

00:10:59.780 --> 00:11:01.880
Start with the essentials, right?

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:05.570
You've got HTML for
structure, CSS for style.

00:11:05.780 --> 00:11:08.120
Then there's JavaScript for interaction.

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:13.220
And if you're working with platforms like
WordPress, PHP Basics can go a long way.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:16.490
That alone is gonna take you
further than most web designers.

00:11:16.535 --> 00:11:17.495
Would ever go.

00:11:17.525 --> 00:11:21.635
I started with free courses on Code
Academy and then I would learn more as

00:11:21.635 --> 00:11:23.675
projects that I worked on needed it.

00:11:23.704 --> 00:11:26.735
And once you get the basics
down, here's the real trick.

00:11:26.765 --> 00:11:32.255
Find solutions that are about 80% of the
way there, and then vibe, code, the rest.

00:11:32.855 --> 00:11:33.995
So what do I mean by that?

00:11:34.025 --> 00:11:37.595
Use code pens or snippets,
even chat GPT, right?

00:11:37.595 --> 00:11:40.475
Whatever gets you close, and
then you just tweak it until

00:11:40.475 --> 00:11:41.855
it does what you want it to do.

00:11:41.915 --> 00:11:45.935
I had a friend who's not a developer
who customized WordPress WooCommerce

00:11:45.935 --> 00:11:50.495
plugin to have a custom checkout
process for his wife's website.

00:11:50.525 --> 00:11:52.625
You don't need to be a
full stack developer.

00:11:52.685 --> 00:11:54.155
You just learn by doing.

00:11:54.265 --> 00:11:57.715
Don't overthink it and use the
tools that are available to you.

00:11:57.775 --> 00:12:02.335
And finally, the fifth skill to
stand out as the top 1% of all

00:12:02.335 --> 00:12:04.735
web designers conversion skills.

00:12:05.245 --> 00:12:10.255
Most designers design for looks,
but pro designers design for action.

00:12:10.314 --> 00:12:14.785
Early in my career, I redesigned
a client's website from the ground

00:12:14.785 --> 00:12:16.765
up and it looked amazing, right?

00:12:16.824 --> 00:12:19.465
Way better than the original.

00:12:19.465 --> 00:12:20.350
But here's the problem.

00:12:21.330 --> 00:12:24.540
After we launched, their sales plummeted.

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:25.439
Why?

00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:31.050
Because I had focused so much on the
design that I ignored the user journey,

00:12:31.439 --> 00:12:34.980
and that was a turning point for me
and a really hard lesson to learn.

00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:39.000
So let's talk about what
conversion thinking really means.

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:41.605
First, every page needs to have.

00:12:41.970 --> 00:12:44.310
Just one goal, right?

00:12:44.550 --> 00:12:45.180
That's it.

00:12:45.180 --> 00:12:46.980
And that goal should be simple.

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:50.880
You either want somebody to buy a
product, sign up for a phone call,

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:53.790
or get a lead magnet, and that's it.

00:12:54.060 --> 00:12:57.900
You lose users when you're
trying to do too much at once.

00:12:57.930 --> 00:12:58.440
Second.

00:12:58.475 --> 00:12:58.775
You.

00:12:58.775 --> 00:13:04.625
You need to have clear strategic CTAs
and they need to be visible within

00:13:04.625 --> 00:13:07.445
seconds of someone landing on the page.

00:13:07.685 --> 00:13:11.885
I like to include a clear CTA
in the hero section, one in the

00:13:11.885 --> 00:13:17.195
navigation, and then one about every
two or three seconds as a user.

00:13:17.195 --> 00:13:17.915
Scroll down.

00:13:18.165 --> 00:13:23.685
Third, it's about trust, clarity,
and maybe most importantly feelings.

00:13:24.135 --> 00:13:28.125
You probably heard it said that
people buy from brands that

00:13:28.125 --> 00:13:30.465
they know, like, and trust.

00:13:30.825 --> 00:13:33.045
But I like to take it one step further.

00:13:33.105 --> 00:13:37.755
They need to know, like, trust
and feel something from you.

00:13:37.875 --> 00:13:40.065
Your site has to speak
to real motivations.

00:13:40.075 --> 00:13:42.985
Clearly explain what they're
getting and it needs to show

